flowchart LR

  subgraph INTENT["1. Path objective"]
    G1["Turn RTDL decision-worthy and audit-worthy outputs into case-intent truth"]
    G2["Keep this path narrower than case creation, case timeline truth, and label truth"]
    G3["Answer which RTDL outcomes deserve operational review work at all"]
  end

  subgraph ENTRY["2. Entry basis"]
    E1["The entry is not raw traffic and not generic RTDL liveness"]
    E2["The entry is the subset of RTDL decision and audit outputs that are eligible to become operational review truth"]
    E3["The path language says the case-escalation path begins from RTDL decision and audit outputs"]
    E4["The Case + Label readiness plan says the plane is proved only after the already-working upstream decision surfaces feed the case-trigger boundary correctly"]
    E5["So this path begins only once RTDL has already produced usable decision and audit truth"]
  end

  subgraph SPINE["5. Broad route logic"]
    R1["RTDL decision and audit outputs"]
    R2["Case-trigger selection and suppression logic"]
    R3["Case-intent truth"]
    R4["Case-trigger topic"]
    R5["Case-management intake"]
  end

  subgraph CARRIES["4. What the path carries"]
    C1["The upstream RTDL decision or audit signal that made the event case-worthy"]
    C2["Run-scope continuity"]
    C3["Enough identity to suppress duplicates correctly"]
    C4["Enough boundary provenance that later case-management and audit surfaces can explain why the case exists at all"]
    C5["The plane must remain fully auditable, duplicate and replay behavior must not corrupt truth, and live telemetry must preserve RTDL-to-case-trigger event movement and run-scope continuity into case and label outputs"]
    C6["This path carries operational truth with continuity obligations, not just open-case please"]
  end

  subgraph LOGIC["6. Logical design reading"]
    L1["The platform treats escalation selection as its own truth boundary"]
    L2["The system is not saying once RTDL emits decisions, case management can decide what matters"]
    L3["There is a dedicated boundary that owns trigger selection"]
    L4["That boundary must be correct, duplicate-safe, and stable under replay"]
    L5["This is how the whole plane preserves truth ownership: case-trigger owns trigger selection, case management owns case timeline truth, and label store owns label truth"]
  end

  subgraph SEATING["7. Concrete seating in the current wired system"]
    S1["The copied baseline wired graphs show a live case-trigger deployment in the case-and-label namespace"]
    S2["The RTDL downstream topic and the audit topic both feed the case-trigger surface"]
    S3["The case-trigger surface publishes case intents into the case-trigger topic"]
    S4["Case management consumes from that topic"]
    S5["So the case-trigger surface has a named workload placement and a named downstream topic boundary"]
    S6["The proving notes retained case-trigger counters: published, duplicates, quarantine, and payload_mismatch_total"]
    S7["That means the platform already treats this boundary as a first-class observable surface rather than burying it inside case management"]
  end

  subgraph RATIONALE["8. Why the design looks like this"]
    Y1["The platform wants a clean escalation boundary before operational case truth begins"]
    Y2["That boundary must choose the right upstream decisions and audit events, avoid false-positive case intent, avoid silent misses, suppress duplicate and replayed trigger creation, and remain stable under bounded production pressure"]
    Y3["Those are exactly the case-trigger requirements that were pinned"]
    Y4["So the shape is not accidental"]
    Y5["It exists because the platform does not want case truth to begin from an undifferentiated stream of RTDL output"]
    Y6["It wants a distinct, owned case-intent surface first"]
  end

  subgraph CONTRACT["9. What larger contracts are shaping this path"]
    X1["The Case + Label component contract shapes what this path must mean: semantic correctness, ownership correctness, duplicate and replay safety, latency and throughput, and auditability"]
    X2["The whole-plane contract shapes why it exists: the right RTDL outputs become case-worthy signals, those signals become the right cases, and no shadow truth ownership appears between case-trigger, case management, and label store"]
    X3["The topic continuity contract shapes the concrete handoff: case-trigger topic, producer = case-trigger surface, consumer = case management"]
    X4["The phase telemetry contract shapes how it must be observed: trigger intake counts, duplicate suppression counters, RTDL-to-case-trigger event movement, and fail-fast if case and label workers are healthy but dark for the current run"]
  end

  subgraph TRADEOFFS["10. Trade-offs and constraints"]
    T1["This path deliberately adds another explicit truth boundary after RTDL"]
    T2["That costs extra structure: one more producer/consumer handoff, one more duplicate-suppression surface, one more place where replay semantics must stay clean, and one more thing to observe live"]
    T3["But that cost buys the ability to separate RTDL emitted decision from this decision deserves operational review"]
    T4["Without that boundary, case management would either have to infer escalation itself or accept too much upstream noise"]
    T5["If case-trigger is wrong, the operational review surface becomes noisy or blind"]
  end

  subgraph NECESSITY["11. Necessity test"]
    N1["If this path is removed, the platform can still ingest traffic, make decisions, append audit truth, and later create cases somehow"]
    N2["But it loses a clean answer to which RTDL outcomes were truly case-worthy"]
    N3["It loses a clean answer to whether duplicate or replayed RTDL outputs should create new operational work"]
    N4["It loses a clean answer to why a case exists at all"]
    N5["It loses a clean answer to whether case management is receiving operational truth or just a flood of undifferentiated machine outputs"]
    N6["That would weaken A immediately because the platform would have RTDL truth and case truth, but no explicit owner for the crucial escalation judgment that connects them"]
    N7["If case-trigger is wrong, the entire operational review surface becomes noisy or blind"]
  end

  subgraph CLOSURE["3. Owned outcome and 12. What this path proves for A"]
    O1["Case-intent truth exists"]
    O2["There is a clean handoff into the case-trigger boundary"]
    O3["The platform has made an explicit, duplicate-safe, replay-stable determination that an upstream decision or audit signal is case-worthy"]
    O4["Owned outcome: case-intent truth before case creation begins"]
    A1["Purpose claim:<br/>the platform has a distinct job for converting RTDL decision and audit truth into case-intent truth before case management begins"]
    A2["Intentionality claim:<br/>escalation selection is explicitly owned by case-trigger rather than inferred later by case management"]
    A3["Materialization claim:<br/>the path is concretely seated in the case-trigger workload and its topic handoff to case management"]
    A4["Contract claim:<br/>this path is governed by trigger precision and recall, duplicate suppression, replay safety, and clean truth ownership"]
    A5["Constraint-awareness claim:<br/>the platform already knows this boundary can fail by noise, blindness, or duplicate explosion, which is why it is measured directly instead of being hidden inside later case-state behavior"]
    A6["Material participation evidence:<br/>the plane-level proving notes retained case-trigger counters published, duplicates, quarantine, and payload_mismatch_total, and the bounded case-and-label closure recorded clean integrity deltas on a large admitted-request slice while the upstream base remained pass"]
    A7["A-level meaning:<br/>RTDL truth becomes explicit case-worthy operational truth through an owned escalation boundary instead of leaving operational review to infer importance from all upstream outputs"]
  end

